It is hypothesized that the "fabricated deity" Takeminakata replaced Suwa's original deity, {{ill|Suwahime|ja|須波神|12=draft|12=draft}}, who was a water deity mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}} during Empress {{ill|Jitō|ja|持統天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}'s reign. This shift occurred because the Kanasashi [[Toneribe]] Clan, who had served Emperor Kinmei, gained control over the Suwa region in the latter half of the 6th century. They collaborated with the {{ill|Moriya clan|ja|守矢氏|1=Moriya clan|12=draft|12=draft}} to conduct rituals, raising their status. This connection is reflected in Takeminakata's promotion within the pantheon.<ref name="#1"/> Furthermore, being closely related to the {{ill|Omi Clan|ja|多氏|1=Ō clan|12=draft|12=draft}}, they allegedly influenced {{ill|Ō no Yasumaro}} to incorporate Takeminakata's myth into the ''Kojiki''.<ref name="#1"/>
From the [[Nara Period]] to the early [[Heian Period]], Shinano's local administration was led by the Kanasashi [[Toneribe]] Clan and {{ill|Tadera Clan|ja|他田部氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. Members of the Kanasashi Clan were prominent as local governors in {{ill|Inagōri District|ja|伊那郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Suwa District|ja|諏訪郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Chiisagata District|ja|小県郡|12=draft|12=draft}}. One key figure was {{ill|Kanasashi Toneri Hachiro|ja|金刺舎人八麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}}, who served as governor of {{ill|Inagōri District|ja|伊那郡|12=draft|12=draft}} and was recognized for suppressing the {{ill|Fujiwara no Nakamaro Rebellion|ja|藤原仲麻呂の乱|12=draft|12=draft}} in 764.<ref>''Shoku Nihongi,'' Volume 25, Emperor Shōtoku, 764 AD</ref>
The Kanasashi Clan maintained strong ties to central authorities through their role in horse breeding, which was essential for both transportation and military purposes. Five of the 16 imperial horse pastures in Shinano Province were located in the southern region.<ref name="#1"/>
== Religious Influence == A branch of the Kanasashi Clan in {{ill|Mizuno District|ja|水内郡|12=draft|12=draft}} is said to have contributed to the establishment of {{ill|Zenkō-ji|ja|善光寺|12=draft|12=draft}}, basing themselves in what is now Nagano City.<ref>Kiriwara, Ken, ''My Notes on Ancient Studies'' (Shinmai Book Center, 1983)</ref>
== Forged Lineages in the "Genealogy of Kami" == The "Genealogy of Kami," kept by the {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}} Shrine, claims that the Kanasashi Clan descended from the {{ill|Shinano Province Clan Leader|ja|科野国造|1=Shina no Kuni no Miyatsuko|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, these genealogies were fabricated during the early modern period to legitimize the clan's identity and connection to the shrine.<ref>Maeda, Ryotaro, "Reconsidering the Genealogies of Suwa Taisha," ''Journal of Japanese Literature and Culture,'' Issue 161 (Hokkaido University, August 2023)</ref>
== Legacy == In the {{ill|Jōgan Era|ja|貞観|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kanasashi Toneri Sadamitsu|ja|金刺舎人貞長|12=draft|12=draft}}, a member of the Kanasashi Clan, was promoted to various positions within the imperial court but later shifted to a religious role within the {{ill|Suwa Taisha}}. This transition illustrates the gradual decline of the clan's political influence in favor of religious and cultural pursuits.
